A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS.
According to a new baseline study, over 3 million people a year die prematurely due to air pollution from outside, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is wood and coal burning for heating housing and cooking, but research reveals that such an alarming reason is the agricultural emissions from Europe and the USA, which are the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that if no measures are taken, the number of dead - already equivalent to six dead per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should trigger an alarm signal for public health agencies around the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by the rain of the air are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
These cause heart attack and heart attack, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million annual deaths, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
Research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause another 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in the journal Nature, is the first to highlight various sources of air pollution from outside and estimated the number of premature deaths they cause, considering road traffic, fossil fuel-based power plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computer model of global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on the various populations, including new information on how pollution affects Chinese and Indian inhabitants.
One third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of fumes, such as wood and coal, for heating or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which were recognized dangers.
Consumption of this type of internal energy results in half of India's 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China's 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Leveld of the German Chemical Institute Max Planck, who led the research.
One fifth of global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and the excess use of fertilisers.
The ammonia reacts with the exhaust gas from the traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, the main reason for the deaths due to air pollution in the east of the USA, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Leslieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of the dead, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of global deaths, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by the power plant, in particular by those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the US, it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55,000 deaths per year, compared to 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in dry and dusty regions, caused almost one-fifth of global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some dry countries, being responsible for 92% of the dead in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The overlap between the high level of pollution and the large number of inhabitants speaks about public health, but nothing is known about the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," says Jerrett.
The results are surprising and potentially important for overall public health protection.
Now all particles are supposed to be as toxic.
But if those caused by combustion of fuels are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, says Jerrett "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and because it suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both by scientists and politicians".
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmospheric specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: "The study really highlights the need for air quality control, to avoid these deaths, especially in the very populated areas of Asia."
