"These studies add to an increasing set of evidence regarding the safety of antidepressants during pregnancy," said John Thorp, Deputy editor-in-chief of the International Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology in a press release, which published all three studies.
Although there are some increased risks, so far the evidence seems to show that the risks of untreated depression are higher than the risks of antidepressant administration.
The Norwegian Institute for Public Health coordinated a study on the motor development of children whose mothers were treated with SSRI, analyzing the data of 51 404 children in the Norwegian cohort study of the mother and child, investigating the effects of SSRI for the development of motor skills at the age of 3 years.
Researchers found that 381 mothers had used SSRI during pregnancy, and 159 of them were treated with prolonged medicines.
Although exposure to SSRI was associated to some extent with a delay in motor development, researchers wrote in the study that the association "was not so significant as to give delay a clinical importance".
A group of researchers at Adelaide University in Australia conducted a data review for 49,000 women in the Danish National Birth Cohort to discover the effects of SSRI on child behaviour up to the age of 7.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk of behavioural problems.
In 210 of the children whose mothers had been treated against SSRI depression, there was no increased risk of behavioural problems compared to 231 children who were most prone to behavioural problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization problems.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more likely to bleed after birth if they are treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30 198 who were born in a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11 and 16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers have reported.
Researchers said that although the study related the administration of SSRI at increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information that researchers had on the specific medical conditions of women - that could have had an effect on the potential for bleeding.
"It is possible that women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy were those with the worst stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressants," says Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
Only on the basis of this study do we recommend that women stop treating drugs against depression during pregnancy, but should be closely monitored to minimise the risk of potential bleeding.
