The study states that the Asia Pacific region already has the largest number of very rich people, known as the High Net Worth Individuals financial jargon, HNWI, with 4.69 million such individuals in 2014, compared to 4.68 million in North America.
HNWI are people who can invest at least a million dollars without taking into account the value of real estate and other possessions.
"In the future, the HNWI fortune is expected to grow more in Asia Pacific than in any other region of the world, most of the new assets coming from the emerging economies of China, India, Indonesia and Thailand", is shown in the study by Capgemini and RBC Wealth Management.
The report estimates that China and India represent almost 10% of the global HNWI fortune and are responsible for 17% of the global growth of new assets after 2006.
China, the second economy of the world after the US, had in 2014 a number of 890.000 millionaires with a cumulative fortune of $4,500 billion, growing 17.5%, or 19.3%, compared to 2013.
In its turn, India has the fastest rate of growth in the number of millionaires, 26.3%, up to 198,000 people, while their cumulative fortune has increased by 28.2%, up to 785 billion dollars.
