Red Flag Uped
The internal scrutiny of Labour seems more spectacular and more significant political, as the new elected leader automatically becomes his spearhead in the upcoming elections.
Raise up, therefore, the red-lit flag/ Under his laps we will live and die.
That was yesterday, Jeremy Corbyn in London's Sanctuary House pub.
He has witnessed many facts and vows/ Let us not change his color now.
Readers who do not know the melodic line of this unofficial British and international left anthem (The Red Flag/ Red Flag) can search it online and would not be excluded to have a surprise.
With the heads discovered, let's all swear/that we'll wear it until we collapse.
The author of these lines is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and of those who fly them), but respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn manages to unite the left of yesterday with the one of tomorrow, this love story between him and the Labour Party's base will be part of a happy end.
I don't think this will happen, but it seems premature to talk about the sea and the inevitable electoral defeat, in five years' time, of a leader chosen from the other day.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have witnessed a democratic exercise of an impressive size.
British Labour has not invented the system of direct voting for the party's leader, left-wing.
The French Socialists have been practicing a more complicated system for several years, based on motions, which allows the expression of all members and sympathizers; in addition, they have organised a preliminary competition for the appointment of the presidential candidate in 2012.
However, the internal election of the Labour seems more spectacular and more significant political, as the new elected leader automatically becomes his spearhead in the future elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, with the personalization of power being more pronounced in Britain than on the other side of the Channel.
In addition, participation in the vote was high in all three "circles": the members themselves, the members of the trade unions and other organizations affiliated to the party and, finally, the group of sympathizers (who received the ballot paper after a summary registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of the left segments of British society, especially those of young and middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to get even more involved in the future, just because of the signal offered by Corbyn’s victory.
There are no sociological investigations to tell us too much about the attitudes of this Labour "external search", so careful speculation is allowed.
I think we are seeing a lot of attitudes similar to those of the sympathizers Podemos (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will travel through the traditional channels of the left.
If we tend to identify a vocation "anti-system", it is primarily reflected by rejecting the centrist line, New Labour (for many, only a dissimulated form of much-healing thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty of the two successive electoral failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go far enough to the left, that they did not delimit themselves firmly from the time of Tony Blair.
The second point - after me, and more suggestive - is offered by the recent referendum on Scotland's independence.
If we abstain from the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations for other political issues, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of public segments favourable to the social state and animated by the aspiration of equity, followers of disarmament and hostile military involvement abroad, but also sensitive to new left-wing themes: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
Scottish workers have thus lost an electorate to whom they should have, at least in principle, privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbyn's campaign).
Such energies exist everywhere in the United Kingdom, but the old leadership could not attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation of outsider, has more chance of success than Ed Miliband, the "aristocrat" Labour.
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I believe, than with the left anti-system in the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "antisystem" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
By next week we will learn more about Jeremy Corbyn's first steps as leader of the opposition.
We'll see if the Red Flag will also rise in the House of Commons (it wouldn't be for the first time), after the new leader takes over the place, first of the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbyn wants now from his colleagues in Parliament is first and foremost unity - and in this regard he has reason to be concerned.
